(227, 'UK-CRS-804a', NULL, '35', 'UK-CRS-804a - all energy use', 'all energy use', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1100', NULL, '1100', NULL, '1100', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Cross-cutting', NULL, 'Synthesis of Climate Change Policy Appraisals', NULL, 'GB Submission 07', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(228, 'UK-ENS-03', NULL, '36', 'Combined heat and power', 'Achieve at least 10 gigawatts (GW) of Good Quality CHP capacity by 2010', 'In 2002 Government published the UK&rsquo;s Strategy for Combined Heat and Power to 2010, setting out a framework to support the growth of CHP capacity in the UK. The 2003 Energy White Paper reiterated the UK&rsquo;s intention to continue to promote CHP and reaffirmed the UK&rsquo;s commitment to its target of achieving at least 10 gigawatts (GW) of Good Quality CHP   capacity by 2010. <br />Due in the main to adverse market conditions in recent years, the UK is over halfway towards the target, with over 5.5GW of installed capacity by the end of 2005. <br />The costs of generating electricity using CHP are often higher than for standard centralised generation, even though there is a financial return for the heat that can be sold.  To reward the carbon saving CHP offers, and to encourage the growth of CHP capacity in the UK, Government has introduced a number of support measures, including:<br />&bull; Favourable allowance allocations under phase II of the EU ETSExemption from the Climate Change Levy <br />&bull; Business Rates exemption <br />&bull; Enhanced capital allowances for plant and equipment<br />&bull; ROC eligibility for the biomass element of fuel used in energy from waste plants that utilise CHP<br />The UK Government continues to monitor progress towards the CHP target and works in active partnership with industry to ensure the cost-effective delivery of the UK CHP Strategy.', '2002', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.7/8', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
