(229, 'UK-ENS-04', NULL, '37', 'Micro-generation', 'To create conditions under which microgeneration becomes a realistic alternative or supplementary energy generation source for the householder, the community and small business', 'The microgeneration strategy was published in March 2006. It commits to tackling barriers currently preventing widespread take-up, including issues around planning permission, costs of installing microgeneration, lack of information and technical constraints.<br />The strategy forms part of the Government&#39;s wider energy policy as set out in the Government&#39;s Energy White Paper &#39;Our energy future - creating a low carbon economy&rsquo;. Microgeneration has a significant role to play in meeting our energy policy goal of sustainable and secure energy for all. A study carried out by the Energy Saving Trust indicated that by 2050 microgeneration could be providing around 30-40% of the UK&rsquo;s electricity needs, reducing carbon emissions by 15% per annum.<br />Key measures in the strategy include:<br />&bull; The Low Carbon Buildings Programme (LCBP) was launched in April 2006, offering &pound;30 million in capital grants over 3 years to successful applicants with a further &pound;50 million made available at Budget 06. The main objectives are to use the &pound;80 million as a demonstration platform for encouraging both energy-efficiency and microgeneration technologies in a range of buildings, driving down costs in the process, and making the microgeneration market more sustainable<br />&bull; Other measures to tackle upfront costs include helping microgenerators gain better access to the rewards for generating electricity.  For example, easier access to Renewable Obligation Certificates and better rewards for electricity exported to the grid.<br />&bull; Communications is a key issue.  We will be reviewing existing communications efforts to assess their effectiveness.  We will also be looking at targeting information &ndash; in particular working with planners in local authorities and the construction industry. <br />&bull; Planning policy has an important role to play.  Microgeneration is encouraged through the Code for Sustainable Homes. DCLG are looking at the Householder Consents Regime to assess what steps need to be taken to facilitate the installation of microgeneration on existing houses. Planning Policy Statement 22 (PPS22) encourages local authorities and developers to consider onsite renewable energy projects. A review of submitted plans was carried out in 2006 and found that the majority did contain renewable energy policies and numbers were increasing alongside further promotion.<br />&bull; The development of a robust certification scheme to build consumer trust in products and installers. A code of practice for renewables will be a key element of this.<br />The Scottish Executive has invested an additional &pound;16 million in grant funding for microgeneration through the Scottish Community and Household Renewables Initiative. <br />The Welsh Assembly Government is publishing a Microgeneration Action Plan in March 2007 and has been consulting on amendments to planning policy.  It is also piloting microgeneration installation as part of the Home Energy Efficiency Scheme.', '2006', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.8/9', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(230, 'UK-ENS-05', NULL, '38', 'Carbon abatement technology strategy', 'Cleaner and better technologies', 'Government has allocated &pound;35m for the demonstration of Carbon Abatement Technologies, which include both cleaner coal and carbon capture and storage technologies.<br />The Energy Review (2006) made clear that the next logical step for carbon capture and storage would be to build a full-scale demonstration plant in the UK, subject to it being cost-effective. The consulting engineers appointed to look at the costs of building a Carbon Capture and Storage plant based in the UK have now reported. A decision on whether to commit to a demonstration project will be made later this year.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.9', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(231, 'UK-ENS-06', NULL, '39', 'Coalmine methane', 'Control coalmine methane emissions', 'Measures to abate methane from working coal mines are in place in the UK, but the 2003 Energy White Paper noted the environmental problem created by emissions of methane from disused coal mines and stated that more was needed to control coal mine methane (CMM) emissions.<br />Although the production of electricity from CMM was exempted from the climate change levy in 2003, plans to introduce a grant scheme to support projects aimed at controlling CMM emissions have had to be postponed because of funding constraints.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.9', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(232, 'UK-ENS-07', NULL, '40', 'Micro-CHP', 'Increase use of micro-CHP', 'Micro-CHP offers the potential for significant reductions in household energy bills and carbon emissions.  We support the development of this new technology and the potential it offers for significant energy savings. Micro-CHP forms part of our CHP Strategy and we estimate it has the potential to contribute between 300 and 500 mega watt equivalent (Mwe) to the 2010 target.<br />Under EEC II (2005-2008), we are incentivising the development of innovative products, including micro-CHP units with a maximum electrical capacity of up to 50 kilowatts. This incentive credits energy suppliers with an additional 50 per cent of energy savings, up to a maximum of 10 per cent of their EEC target. <br />As part of the review of EEC in 2007, which will include setting the target for the proposed EEC 2008-2011, we will take account of the outcome of the field trials in deciding whether to continue any incentive for micro-CHP under the EEC, and if so at what level', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.29', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(233, 'UK-TRA-08', NULL, '41', 'Transport strategy', 'Balance the increasing demand for travel against our goal of protecting the environment effectively and improving the quality of life for everyone', 'In July 2004 , the UK Government set out its transport strategy in &ldquo;The Future of Transport: a network for 2030&rdquo; White Paper.  This made clear that while good transport is central to a prosperous economy, facilitating better access and greater mobility, we must balance the increasing demand for travel against our goal of protecting the environment effectively and improving the quality of life for everyone &ndash; whether they are traveling or not. <br />This strategy has been followed by the UK Climate Change Programme (2006), and the Energy Review, which further set out our efforts to tackle greenhouse gas emissions from transport.<br />Many aspects of transport are devolved, and policies in this sector are taken forward at a combination of devolved or UK-wide levels.  Scotland&rsquo;s National Transport Strategy  was published in December 2006; reducing emissions is one of its three strategic outcomes.<br />The consultation on the Welsh Assembly Government&rsquo;s new, statutory Transport Strategy has just ended, with tackling climate change as a key theme.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.17', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(234, 'UK-TRA-09', NULL, '42', 'Fiscal measures', 'Move to a low carbon transport system and encouraging the purchase and use of fuel efficient vehicles', 'The UK considers that fiscal measures are a key tool for achieving a move to a low carbon transport system and encouraging the purchase and use of fuel efficient vehicles. These complement action at the EU level through the Voluntary Agreements with car manufacturers.<br />Since 1997, the Government has radically reformed its main vehicle taxation policies to encourage the purchase and use of clean, low carbon vehicles and fuels. Both vehicle excise duty (VED) and company car tax are now based on vehicles&rsquo; carbon dioxide emissions. <br />The Government published the Alternative Fuels Framework as part of the Pre-Budget Report in 2003. This set out the Government&rsquo;s commitment to promoting sustainable alternatives for fossil fuels. The Framework committed the Government to a three-year rolling guarantee for biofuels and road fuel gas duty rates, offering certainty to support investment. The UK Government&rsquo;s 2006 Budget announced that the 20 pence per litre duty incentive for bioethanol and biodiesel would be maintained to 2008&ndash;09.<br />The Government remains committed to using economic instruments, such as taxation, as a way of reducing the environmental impact of road transport. The Government will continue to evaluate the existing suite of measures, and keep under review the possibility of new measures in the future, as part of the normal Budget process.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.17/18', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(235, 'UK-TRA-10', NULL, '43', 'Developing and promoting new vehicle technologies', 'To promote the development, introduction and take-up of new vehicle technologies and fuels; and<br />To ensure the full involvement of the UK automotive industry in the new technologies.', 'New vehicle technologies and fuels offer opportunities for radically reducing the impact of road transport on the environment. The UK&rsquo;s Powering Future Vehicles Strategy (PFV), published in July 2002, sets out our aspiration that the UK should lead the global shift to the low-carbon transport economy, building competitive advantage for our automotive industries.  The main objectives of the Strategy are: <br />&bull; to promote the development, introduction and take-up of new vehicle technologies and fuels; and<br />&bull; to ensure the full involvement of the UK automotive industry in the new technologies.<br />The Government is currently undertaking a review of the PFV Strategy taking into account recent developments and reports across Government and changes in technologies.<br />The UK Government has directly supported the development and uptake of clean, low carbon vehicles through grant programmes run by the Energy Saving Trust.  The EST manage the grant programmes for Low Carbon Research &amp; Development, Infrastructure and Fleet Advice.   The purpose of the grants has been to provide pump priming to the market for cleaner vehicles by supporting their initial market uptake, and to help generate greater awareness and confidence in new technologies.    The programmes have been successful in a number of areas, and complement other measures to incentivise cleaner vehicles such as low fuel duty rates for road fuel gases and graduated company car tax levels according to carbon dioxide levels.  The grants have helped develop the market for cleaner gas powered vehicles and have also supported the uptake of hybrid/electric vehicles.<br />But the grant programmes can only provide initial support for cleaner vehicle technologies in the market place.  With new car sales in excess of two million per year any ongoing fleet-wide grant programmes would be prohibitively expensive and ultimately new technologies will need to compete on a level playing field if they are to achieve significant penetration into mass markets.  The grant programmes will need to comply with the European Commission&rsquo;s rules on state aid to ensure they do not unnecessarily distort internal markets.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.18', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(236, 'UK-TRA-11', NULL, '44', 'Aviation', 'Tackle aviation emissions', 'During its Presidency of the European Union in 2005, the UK made the inclusion of aviation in the EU ETS scheme a priority. Under the UK&rsquo;s chairmanship, the EU Environment Council agreed that emissions trading seemed to be the best way forward. Following this decision, the European Commission took forward work through an Aviation Working Group in the European Climate Change Programme and consequently published a legislative proposal in December 2006.<br />Member states have now begun to discuss the key elements of the proposal through working groups. The UK looks to the Portuguese and Slovenian Presidencies to give this issue priority in the coming months.<br />The UK is also supporting other measures to tackle aviation emissions including:<br />? the adoption of working practices that minimize the impact of the activities from airports, airlines and air traffic controllers;<br />? R&amp;D by aerospace manufacturers to reduce the climate impact of future aircraft; and<br />? Voluntary action by the aviation sector to control greenhouse gas emissions and develop sustainability strategies.<br />Carbon offsetting of emissions from air travel is also being encouraged as part of a hierarchy of measures. In January 2007, the UK Government launched a public consultation on the development of a voluntary standard for offsetting.  The proposed standard and associated code of practice aims to provide consistency in the offsetting industry and clarity for those choosing to offset their carbon emissions.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.19/20', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(237, 'UK-ENC-32', NULL, '45', 'Economic instruments', 'Increase use of energy saving materials, install energy efficiency installations (insulation)', 'Existing instruments already in place include reduced VAT on the installation of domestic energy saving materials from April 2000 for commercially installed energy efficiency installations, most notably insulation.  The UK Government consulted on economic instruments for improving household energy efficiency in 2003 and in 2004 we announced a reduced rate of VAT for the domestic installation of ground source heat pumps; a landlord&rsquo;s energy saving allowance; that we would continue to negotiate with EU partners to extend the categories of permitted reduced VAT rates to include the purchase of energy saving materials for DIY installation.  The Government has indicated that fiscal measures have a useful role in the integrated package of policy instruments to improve energy efficiency and further fiscal incentives for incentivise high environmental standards as an instrument for securing further development are routinely considered as part of the Chancellor&rsquo;s ongoing review of all tax policy.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.26/27', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(238, 'UK-ENC-33', NULL, '46', 'Decent homes', 'Ensure that all social homes are made decent by 2010', 'In 2001 we set a target to ensure that all social homes are made decent by 2010.  We are still committed to making all homes decent but some estates will take a little longer than where the scale of work to deliver mixed communities, or more new build, is significant;<br />To be classed as decent, a home must provide a reasonable degree of thermal comfort, which means it must have effective insulation and efficient heating. Improvements to insulation and heating are a major focus of the decent homes refurbishment works. Of the 1.6 million social homes, which were non-decent in 2001, 1.3 million (80 per cent) will require improvements to their insulation and/or heating systems in order to meet the target.<br />We are making progress.  According to local authority and registered social landlords estimates show that by April 2006 we had achieved an estimated reduction of 41 per cent in non-decent social homes to 976,000.  In the period from 2000-01 to 2004-05 local authorities report that over 470,000 dwellings have received work to improve their energy efficiency under the Decent Homes programme, or as part of wider local authority work to update the stock.  Research by the Building Research Establishment on the implementation of the Decent Homes programme indicates that the majority of improvement works under the Decent Homes scheme include work to improve energy efficiency.  The same research also indicates that most landlords, when implementing energy efficiency works, deliver much higher standards than the minimum required by the Decent Homes Standard.<br />Decent Homes is not just about social housing.  The UK needs to make progress in the private sector.  For owner occupiers and private landlords, we believe that the responsibility for ensuring the property is maintained to a reasonable standard should rest primarily with the owner.  But we believe we must act to protect vulnerable homeowners and tenants who are not in a position to afford the necessary work or are unable to afford better accommodation. The new landlord&rsquo;s energy saving allowance, announced in November 2004 will encourage private landlords to invest in the insulation of their properties.<br />Together with programmes such as Warm Front, measures under decent homes will help to deliver our target to increase the proportion of vulnerable households in the private sector who live in decent homes from 57 per cent in 2001 to 65 per cent by 2006, 70 per cent by 2010.  We had achieved 66 per cent of vulnerable households in decent homes by 2005.  This means that the interim target of 65 per cent has already been met and that we are ahead of the trajectory to meet the 2010 target of 70 per cent.<br />The Scottish Executive has set a target that all social housing will meet the SHQS, including the requirements on effective insulation and efficient central heating by 2015.<br />The Welsh Assembly Government has established the Welsh Housing Quality Standard (WHQS), which local authorities and registered social landlords must meet in their own stock by 2012.  The WHQS states that &ldquo;All cost-effective opportunities to upgrade the thermal and ventilation performance of the dwelling must be taken&rdquo; and sets minimum standards for the annual energy consumption for space and water heating using the SAP methodology.', '2001', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.29/30', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(239, 'UK-ENC-34', NULL, '47', 'Sustainable communities', 'Ensure that homes are built in a way that minimizes the use of energy and reduces these harmful emissions.', 'In 2004, more than a quarter of the UK&rsquo;s carbon dioxide emissions &ndash; a major cause of climate change &ndash; came from the energy we use to heat, light and run our homes.  So it is vital to ensure that homes are built in a way that minimizes the use of energy and reduces these harmful emissions.<br />Construction and use of our homes has a range of other environmental impacts, created for example through water use, waste generation and use of polluting materials, which can be significantly reduced through the integration of higher sustainability performance standards within the design of a home.  More sustainable homes can also provide us with improved overall well-being and quality of life.<br /> The Code for Sustainable Homes has been introduced as a voluntary standard from April 2007 to drive a step-change in sustainable home building practice. It is a standard for key elements of design and construction which affect the sustainability of a new home.  It will become the single national standard for sustainable homes, used by home designers and builders as a guide to development, and by home-buyers to assist in their choice of home.<br />It forms the basis for future improvements to Part L of the Building Regulations (in relation to carbon emissions from, and energy use in homes), therefore offering greater regulatory certainty to developers.  And in this era of environmental awareness amongst consumers and increasing demand for a more sustainable product, it will offer a tool for developers to differentiate themselves.', '2007', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.30/31', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(240, 'UK-ENC-35', NULL, '48', 'Energy services', 'Improve energy efficiency trhough energy services', 'The term &lsquo;energy services&rsquo; broadly means the supply of the services and benefits that energy provides, such as heat and light.  Energy services offer a number of benefits which complement the established social, economic and environmental benefits of energy efficiency in general including innovative financing mechanisms, greater competitive opportunities for utilities; and access to sources of capital to invest in energy efficiency improvements in social housing stock.<br />The Energy Services Working Group (ESWG),  whose final report to Ministers was published in July 2004, addressed, among other issues, the perceived barriers caused by the current 28-day notice period and the need to maintain adequate freedom of choice and consumer protection for customers. <br />The 28-day rule is the license requirement on gas and electricity suppliers that gives a householder the right to terminate their energy supply contract by giving 28 days notice. This was considered essential in the development of the competitive market.  However, suppliers have said they are reluctant to provide energy efficiency measures at no initial cost to their customers who can change supplier at short notice.<br />In its July 2006 consultation, as part of the Supply Licence Review, Ofgem proposed removing the 28-day rule for domestic supply contracts.  This should free suppliers to develop innovative offerings to customers with notice periods appropriate under general consumer protection legislation.  Following a final decision document and proposals for collective licence modification process, Ofgem plans to implement the new supply licences in June 2007.', '2007', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.31', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(241, 'UK-ENC-36', NULL, '49', 'Energy service directive', 'Enhance the cost effective improvement of energy end use efficiency', 'Member States have until 17 May 2008 to fully implement the Directive, which has the purpose of enhancing the cost effective improvement of energy end use efficiency. The Directive covers all forms of energy and applies to providers of energy efficiency measures, energy distributors, distribution system operators and retail energy sales companies; and all energy users except those involved with the EU carbon emissions trading scheme. <br />A Project Board comprising Government Departments, the Devolved Administrations and Ofgem has been set up to steer implementation. This is being taken forward through a number of workstreams, each dealing with a different area of the Directive. Consultation processes have started with that for billing and metering running between November 2006 and February 2007. The results are currently being analysed', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.31', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(242, 'UK-ENC-37', NULL, '50', 'Energy service company', 'Reduce carbon foot print of key cities', 'The UK Government is pursuing a work programme with the local authorities in key cities to reduce their carbon footprints. As part of this we are examining the potential to develop partnerships between the cities and Energy Service Companies delivering low-carbon energy services. We are adopting a broad definition of the kind of energy services that might be delivered, including green energy supply, provision of energy efficiency and microgeneration products, advice and financing. This would include the provision of services to the less-well-off and the able-to-pay sectors.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.32', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(243, 'UK-ENC-38', NULL, '51', 'Energy saving trust', 'Increasing demand for energy efficiency in households through raising awareness, providing advice and support for action.', 'The Energy Saving Trust  (EST) is a private, non-profit organization funded by Government and the devolved administrations, as well as by the private sector.  EST receives grant funding of around &pound;27 million each year for its energy efficiency work. <br /><br />EST activities are aimed at increasing demand for energy efficiency in households through raising awareness, providing advice and support for action.  The Trust also supports the supply of energy efficiency products and services to meet this demand by developing partnerships, stimulating innovation, supporting training and providing accreditation.<br />The Trust runs a wide range of programmes to deliver energy efficiency solutions to householders. These are grouped under 5 headings and consist of:<br />Consumer advice: <br />&bull; A consumer marketing campaign which is the source of information and call to action for consumers to reduce their energy use and install energy efficient measures.  <br />&bull; Energy Efficiency Advice Centres, which provide advice to consumers to help them assess their energy use and refer them on to any available grant offers. <br />&bull; A pilot Sustainable Energy Network, (giving advice on renewable energy and transport as well as energy efficiency)<br />Trade Measures: <br />&bull; accreditation of products under the Energy Saving Recommended label, which signposts consumers to products that save the most energy, and working with trade bodies and retailers<br />&bull; Support in delivery of the Energy Efficiency Commitment<br />&bull; Groundwork in connection with the Home Condition Report<br />&bull; Energy Efficiency Best Practice programme<br />Community Partnerships:<br />&bull; for local authorities and registered social landlords, EST administers a number of programmes including Practical Help, a tailored source of information and support on delivering energy efficiency to their communities <br />&bull; Local Support Service, providing more bespoke advice  <br />&bull; Community Action for Energy (CAFE) which facilitates and supports community-based sustainable energy projects  <br />&bull; Regional activity<br />Underpinning activities:<br />&bull; Energy Efficiency Partnership for Homes, a network of over 395 organisations from the public, private and voluntary sectors.  It works together to promote energy efficiency and reduce fuel poverty.<br />&bull; The Homes Energy Efficiency Database, detailing the uptake of energy efficiency measures. <br />&bull; A Web Information Service that brings together sources of energy efficiency information in a &lsquo;one stop shop&rsquo; approach.<br />Monitoring, Evaluation, research and Analysis:<br />&bull; Evaluation of all programmes<br />&bull; Energy Monitoring of household measures in-situ<br />&bull; Energy Analysis from English House Condition Survey', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.32/33', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(244, 'UK-IND-01', NULL, '52', 'IPPC', 'Energy efficiency and emissions reduction of methane, nitrous oxide, hydrofluorocarbons and perfluorocarbons', 'There are around 5,000 industrial installations in the UK, which are subject to the Integrated Pollution Prevention and Control (IPPC) Directive . They need a permit to operate, which must contain conditions that, amongst other things, require energy to be used efficiently.  The UK&rsquo;s regulators have produced guidance on how this requirement is to be met.  This guidance is currently in the final stages of revision to take account of the availability in the EU Emissions Trading Scheme Directive of a dispensation that Member States need not apply energy efficiency requirements in IPPC permits for installations covered by that Directive. The implementation of IPPC also provides a regulatory basis for reducing emissions of methane, nitrous oxide, hydrofluorocarbons and perfluorocarbons.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.15', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(245, 'UK-CRS-802', NULL, '53', 'EU emission Trading Scheme 2008-2012', 'Securing least cost emissions reductions across the EU', 'The UK National Allocation Plan (NAP) for Phase I (2005-2007) demonstrates commitment to moving beyond our Kyoto target and towards our national goal, whilst also taking a common sense and pragmatic approach to the implementation of this new scheme.<br />The NAP set a total cap of 736.3 MtCO2 (245MtC/yr) allowances for Phase I. This represents a saving of 65MtCO2 (roughly 8 per cent) below the projected emissions of the installations covered by the scheme during Phase I.<br />Though the EU ETS is a mandatory scheme for all installations carrying out Schedule 1 activities, some installations were able to opt-out from the EU ETS. The Directive allows for applications for temporary exclusion for installations in Phase I, providing equivalent emissions reductions, monitoring and reporting and penalties are imposed through other measures.<br />The UK was granted a temporary exclusion for 59 installations currently participating in the UK Emissions Trading Scheme. These Direct Participants of the UK ETS were required to join the EU ETS from January 2007 onwards. Temporary exclusion was also been granted to 331 installations covered by Climate Change Agreements (CCAs). These installations will be required to join the Scheme for Phase II.', '2005', '2007', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.12', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(246, 'UK-CRS-803', NULL, '54', 'EU Linking directive', 'Allow member states to provide for credits for emissions reductions earned through the Kyoto project mechanisms', 'The Emissions Trading Directive was amended by the Linking Directive to allow member states to provide for credits for emissions reductions earned through the Kyoto project mechanisms to be used for compliance with the EU ETS. Regulations (SI 2005/2903) transposing the Linking Directive into UK law entered into force on 13 November 2005. These allow EU ETS operators to use credits generated from the Kyoto flexible mechanisms (the Clean Development Mechanism &ndash; CDM &ndash; and Joint Implementation &ndash; JI) to meet their compliance commitments under the EU ETS.', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.13', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(247, 'UK-ENC-30', NULL, '56', 'Energy performance commitment', 'Cut carbon dioxide emissions from large non-energy intensive commercial and public sector organisations by 4.4 million tonnes per year by 2020.', 'In the Energy Review, the Government committed to consult on measures to cut carbon dioxide emissions from large non-energy intensive commercial and public sector organisations by 4.4 million tonnes per year by 2020.  The consultation included a proposal for an Energy Performance Commitment  (EPC) &ndash; a mandatory emissions trading scheme &ndash; alongside a system of voluntary benchmarking, to achieve the carbon reduction aims for this sector (which includes supermarket chains, hotel chains, and government departments). These organisations account for around 55 MtCO2 of carbon emissions &ndash; about 10 per cent of the UK&rsquo;s economy wide carbon emissions.  <br />The focus of the proposed EPC is on emissions from energy use by large non-energy intensive organisations covering emissions outside the EU Emissions Trading Scheme and Climate Change Agreements.  The proposed EPC would be much &ldquo;lighter touch&rdquo; than the EU ETS, relying on self-certification of emissions backed up by audit. In-depth analysis indicates that, by focusing on energy efficiency, the proposed EPC would deliver emissions reductions cost-effectively, saving business money, and enabling green growth.<br />The consultation ended on 31st January and the responses are currently being analysed.  Ministers are set to make a decision on the most appropriate way to achieve the emissions reductions in the Spring of 2007.', '2007', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4400', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.13/14', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(248, 'UK-ENC-31', NULL, '57', 'Climate Change Communications Initiative', 'Effective climate change communication', 'The initiative also provides free resources, including the www.climatechallenge.gov.uk website, a guide to effective climate change communication, an award-winning 2-minute film (distributed as a TV filler, a DVD and on-line), and results of specially-commissioned attitude surveys.<br />Large scale national activities have also been seen as an important part of the strategy - to give national identity, and allowing local-level activities to feel part of a wider, Government-backed initiative. We also want to add value to other campaigns and activities planned by NGOs, business and media players. We are therefore developing information tools to help individuals better understand their relationship with carbon, and to take action to reduce their emissions; <br />In addition, in 2006 a competition was run to choose 9 youth champions, who are now working regionally, and in some instances nationally, to highlight the need to tackle climate change. These young people act as figureheads for the initiative, drawing in additional publicity, working with schools and local government, and adding value to the CCF projects. They have gained significant national and regional media attention.<br />We have announced that we are developing a carbon calculator, which we plan to launch later in the spring. This will help individuals understand the scale of their carbon emissions, and the different components that make up their footprint include domestic heating and appliance use. It will use data agreed across Government. <br />We will also shortly launch a consultation on a Code of Best Practice for offsetting products. The Code will give individuals greater assurance that offsetting products they are purchasing do &quot;what they say on the label,&quot; and will address types of credits, information to the consumer and calculation methodologies, for example. In addition, we also plan to produce a second short film intended to help make the link between climate change, carbon, and individual behaviour in the home and around personal transport. <br />In addition to developing these information tools, we will over the next months be promoting the spread of carbon dioxide &ldquo;literacy&rdquo; in our communications. We want to raise awareness that we all emit CO2 in our everyday lives and therefore have some sort of carbon footprint. We will be contracting an advertising agency and PR firm to help spread this message and drive people to the information tools we are developing. We will also be developing a new &ldquo;call to action&rdquo; brand around CO2, to run in conjunction with the existing &ldquo;Tomorrow&rsquo;s Climate, Today&rsquo;s Challenge&rdquo; brand, which ties together the different activities funded by Government in this area. <br />The Welsh Assembly Government has undertaken an initial communications campaign focused on practical advice to members of the public about the action they can take to address climate change.  Activity has included the development of a dedicated resource on the Assembly Government website, radio adverts focusing on energy efficiency and car sharing, PR activity to raise the profile of practical actions that everyone can take to tackle climate change in local newspapers, as well as roadshow events and a schools competition.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.24/25', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(249, 'UK-ENC-39', NULL, '58', 'Salix finance', 'Reduce carbon emissions from public sector', 'Salix Finance is a not-for-profit company set up by the Carbon Trust in 2004 to help the public sector reduce its own carbon emissions.  Salix operates through ring-fenced recycling funds, within public sector organisations, with matched funding from both parties. In the Pre Budget Report 2005 Salix was granted a &pound;20m increase in funding.', '2004', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.41', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(250, 'UK-ENC-40', NULL, '59', 'The Government Estate', 'To reduce carbon emissions from the office based estate by 30 per cent by 2020', 'A range of new government sustainability targets, including a pledge that the Government office estate will go carbon neutral by 2012, were announced on the 12 June 2006 by Environment Secretary David Miliband. As part of its commitment to giving a lead on environmentally sustainable behavior to business and consumers, the Government has set an aspirational target to reduce carbon emissions from the office based estate by 30 per cent by 2020.<br />Carbon emissions from offices: <br />&bull; Reverse the current upward trend in carbon emissions by April 2007. <br />&bull; Reduce carbon emissions by 12.5% by 2010-11, relative to 1999/2000 levels. <br />&bull; Reduce carbon emissions by 30% by 2020, relative to 1999/2000 levels. <br />Carbon neutral <br />&bull; Central Government&rsquo;s office estate to be carbon neutral by 2012<br />Energy efficiency: <br />&bull; Departments to increase their energy efficiency per m&sup2; by 15% by 2010, relative to 1999/2000 levels. <br />&bull; Departments to increase their energy efficiency per m&sup2; by 30% by 2020, relative to 1999/2000 levels. <br />Existing sustainable operational commitments (to continue until completion):<br />&bull; Departments to source at least 10% of electricity from renewables (31 March 2008) <br />&bull; Departments to source at least 15% of electricity from Combined Heat and Power (2010) <br />Energy efficiency in the Government estate has improved by 2% against the baseline.  Six governments have made significant progress but 14 departments are less energy efficient than in 1999/00.<br />Overall carbon emissions since 1999/00 have fallen by 0.5%. However, there remains a great deal to be done to meet the 12.5% reduction by 2010/11.<br />The Government estate is sourcing 23% of its electricity from renewable sources between 2005/06.  This is an increase of 3% from 2004/05.<br />All nine of the departments that have initiated new estate management contracts since August 2004 have included clauses to ensure opportunities are identified, and measures are taken to reduce carbon dioxide emissions, leading to greater improvements in the management of the Estate in the future.<br />The Welsh Assembly Government has just embarked on a project to assess its emission footprint from its estate and official travel to inform the development of an action plan to address it and met the First Minister&rsquo;s commitment to becoming carbon neutral in this area.', '2004', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.41/42', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(251, 'UK-ENC-41', NULL, '60', 'Sustainable Procurement Action Plan', 'Government offices and public services will  become low carbon, low waste and water efficient', 'In march 2007 the Government launched the Sustainable Procurement Action Plan , which sets itself a series of goals, including becoming an EU leader in sustainable procurement by 2009. It outlines how government offices and public services will  become low carbon, low waste and water efficient, as well as respecting biodiversity and delivering wider sustainable development goals including the sustainable operations targets set out above. The public sector purchasing power will be harnessed to transform the market for innovative and sustainable solutions, to make them more affordable and widely available.', '2007', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.42', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(252, 'UK-ENC-42', NULL, '61', 'Schools', 'Increasing the efficiency of the school building stock', 'The education sector is important for the opportunities the curriculum offers to inform young people about climate change and the steps they can take to combat it.  But, in addition, the education sector accounts for approximately 10 per cent of carbon emissions for all commercial and public buildings. <br />The Building Schools for the Future (BSF) programme provides a valuable opportunity for increasing the efficiency of the school building stock. The Government has adopted &#39;BREEAM Schools&#39;, an adaptation of an internationally recognised environmental assessment method.   A building can achieve a &#39;Pass&#39;, &#39;Good&#39;, &#39;Very Good&#39; or an &#39;Excellent&#39; rating, based on a wide-ranging performance criteria that covers energy used in the servicing and construction of a building, health or internal comfort levels for occupants, impact on the landscape and promotion of the use of public.  A prerequisite for schools realised under the Government Building Schools for the Future (BSF) programme is that designs achieve a BREEAM &#39;Very Good&#39; rating. This provides a strong incentive for design teams to consider options to reduce carbon emissions through energy efficiency measures and renewable energy systems.<br />The Energy Efficiency Certification for Schools   scheme also promotes a whole school approach to energy efficiency. This whole school approach helps to ensure the efficient use of school energy resources and to establish positive links between the school curriculum and energy efficiency.<br />In addition, the Carbon Trust promotes a programme aimed at schools via local authority energy managers known as the School Turnkey Energy Programme (STEP), which aims to encourage schools to implement a holistic approach to energy management.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.42/43', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(253, 'UK-ENC-43', NULL, '62', 'The UK&rsquo;s National Health Service (NHS) estate', 'To reduce the level of primary energy consumption by 15 per cent or 0.15 MtC from a base year of March 2000 by March 2010;<br />To achieve a target of 35-55 Gj/100m3 energy efficiency performance for the healthcare estate for all new capital developments and major redevelopments or refurbishments; and that all existing facilities should achieve a target of 55-65 Gj/100m3', 'The NHS has the largest property portfolio in Europe and the biggest capital spend programme. Tasked with building 100 new hospitals and 3,000 GP premises, it emits approximately 1 MtC through its use of energy.<br />The NHS has two targets in England: <br />&bull; to reduce the level of primary energy consumption by 15 per cent or 0.15 MtC from a base year of March 2000 by March 2010;<br />&bull; to achieve a target of 35-55 Gj/100m3 energy efficiency performance for the healthcare estate for all new capital developments and major redevelopments or refurbishments; and that all existing facilities should achieve a target of 55-65 Gj/100m3.<br /> Encode is the primary guidance on energy efficiency in healthcare facilities. It has been produced as a comprehensive guide to all issues relating to the procurement and management of energy in the NHS. Funded by the Carbon Trust and written by the Building Research Establishment (BRE) its aim is to ensure that everyone involved in managing, procuring and using healthcare buildings and equipment thinks about the implications of energy use. It draws together best practice guidance so that healthcare organisations can determine a way forward that best suits their situation. Each NHS trust must already assess its environmental performance using the NHS Environmental Assessment Tool (NEAT), which can also be used to provide criteria for the design process and set design parameters for designers, builders, procurers and operators.  This assessment is ongoing for existing NHS estate buildings and will be a fundamental part of the procurement process for new or refurbished projects.<br />The UK&rsquo;s Department of Health is making additional investment in energy saving measures with the launch of a &pound;100m fund to help improve delivery of energy efficiency.  <br />To continue to improve performance the NHS in Wales has introduced a central energy fund. The allocation of monies to Trusts from this fund is based on approved Trust energy emissions reduction plans for a three-year period starting in 2006/07.  A total sum of &pound;3.1m has been allocated which it is estimated will save 0.01 MtC annually.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.43/44', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(254, 'UK-AGR-09', NULL, '63', 'Common agricultural policy', 'Reduction of emissions from agriculture', 'Two reforms of the Common Agricultural Policy  (CAP) have come into effect since 2000. First, &lsquo;Agenda 2000&rsquo; saw some moderation in support for production subsidies and an increased emphasis on rural development measures including agri-environment schemes.  More significantly, both for changes in the agricultural sector and potential impact on greenhouse gas emissions, the Mid-Term Review reforms agreed in June 2003 made fundamental changes to the subsidy system, decoupling payments to farmers from incentives for production (implemented in England with the introduction of the Single Farm Payment), and making payments conditional on farmers reaching minimum environmental standards on a number of relevant issues.<br />The June 2003 reforms are likely to lead to the detectable changes in agricultural practice from the end of 2005.   There is considerable uncertainty in how farmers might react, but work commissioned by the UK Government  suggests that the reforms might lead to a reduction in greenhouse gas emissions, through;<br />&bull; lower inputs, including artificial fertilizers,<br />&bull; an increase in fallow land leading to less soil disturbance and possible reduction in loss of soil carbon; and<br />&bull; Reductions in livestock numbers that will promote a reduction in greenhouse gas emissions, from animals directly and from manure and slurry handling.<br />Conversely, specialization and concentration in some sectors, especially cereals and dairying, may lead to increases in greenhouse gas emissions, and a shift into high value horticultural or vegetable crops in some areas leading to higher levels of inputs of fertilizers with increased nitrous oxide emissions.  The UK Government will shortly be publishing its Biomass Strategy, which will include details of how it will increase the use of anaerobic digestion.  This will help to mitigate methane emissions from the livestock sector.<br />Cross compliance  (in England) will set a new baseline standard for environmental performance for agriculture that farmers will need to meet to receive their Single Farm Payment.  It is expected that a number of the Good Agricultural and Environmental Condition (GAEC) standards and the measure to maintain levels of permanent pasture will make a modest contribution to emissions reductions by helping improve soil structure and management to maintain organic matter, which will in turn lock-up atmospheric carbon.<br />There are similar cross compliance requirements in Wales.  The Assembly Government has published guidelines on management of agricultural and woodland soils to minimise carbon loss, and these will form part of the Welsh Soil Action Plan.', '2003', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GB subMM19_03_07, p.34', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
