(1182, 'SE-TRA-5', NULL, '37', 'Vehicle tax', 'Persuade car buyers to choose fuel-efficient vehicles and thus reduce carbon dioxide emissions', 'A carbon dioxide-based vehicle tax was introduced in May 2006 to supplement the energy and carbon dioxide taxes. The aim is to persuade car buyers to choose fuel-efficient vehicles to a greater extent than at present and thus to reduce carbon dioxide emissions in traffic. A carbon dioxide-based vehicle tax gives new car buyers an incentive to choose a fuel-efficient vehicle.<br /><br />The carbon-dioxide vehicle tax initially only applies to passenger cars of model year 2006 or later and passenger cars that fulfil at least environmental class 2005, environmental class E1 or environmental class Hybrid. It is intended that other light vehicles will also be covered by the new carbon dioxide-based vehicle tax as soon as possible. <br /><br />The annual vehicle tax is made up of three parts:<br />1. SEK 360 plus<br />2. A carbon dioxide factor of SEK 15/gram carbon dioxide emission per kilometre in excess of 100 grams/km plus<br />3. An environmental factor of 1.3 and a fuel factor of 2.7, total 3.5, for diesel-engined cars, which is to be multiplied by parts 1 and 2. The environmental factor is an extra charge due to higher emissions of particulates and NOx in comparison with petrol-engined vehicles. The fuel factor is an extra charge due to the lower energy tax faced by diesel vehicles in comparison with petrol vehicles. <br /><br />Cars that can run on alternative fuels (fuel-flexible vehicles) are eligible for a SEK 5/gram reduction in the carbon dioxide factor.', '2006', NULL, NULL, 'Non-estimated effect', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'New measure in 2006', 'SE Submission 07, SE subMM15_03_07, Section 2 PAM 2007, p.3', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1183, 'SE-TRA-06', NULL, '38', 'Law on supply of renewable fuels', 'Increased use of renewable fuels', 'A law on the obligation to provide renewable fuels  was introduced on 1 April 2006. This law means that larger filling stations in Sweden must offer renewable fuel for sale alongside petrol and diesel. The expansion will take place gradually between 2006 and 2009, and by 2010 more than 60% of all filling stations will be covered by the law. The law is expected to lead to more rapid development and use of renewable fuels.', '2006', '2009', NULL, 'Non-estimated effect', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'New measure in 2006', 'SE Submission 07, SE subMM15_03_07, Section 2 PAM 2007, p.3', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1184, 'SE-TRA-07', NULL, '39', 'Support for renewable fuels', 'Promote other renewable fuels than ethanol', 'Support for distribution of renewable fuels has been introduced in 2006 and applies to measures carried out from 2006 to 2009 . The support applies to the larger filling stations that are covered by the law on supply of renewable vehicle tax. An aim of this support is to increase the use of renewable fuels, mainly other renewable fuels than ethanol. The support is given to a maximum of 30% of the costs. A total sum of SEK 150 million has been earmarked for the period 2006-2007.', '2006', '2009', NULL, 'Non-estimated effect', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'New measure in 2006', 'SE Submission 07, SE subMM15_03_07, Section 2 PAM 2007, p.3', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1185, 'SI-ENS-01', 'CL-SI-ENS-01', '1', 'IPPC Regulation and EPA for thermal power plants', 'Technological upgrading of thermal power plants', 'The primary aim of the measure is to reduce specific emissions in the generation of electrical power, since given the expected market conditions and the objectives of the Resolution on the National Energy Programme (ReNEP) no short-term reduction in the generation of electrical power can be expected in Slovenia. Despite their relatively good technical state, Slovenian power plants are in need of technological refurbishment, since the majority of facilities are near the end of their life or their efficiency is below the IPPC &ndash; BAT (best available techniques) values. Moreover in Slovenia the proportion of natural gas in fuels used to generate electricity is minimal. Technological upgrading of thermal power plants should contribute to the additional generation of electricity in the amount of 1.5 TWh', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-01', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Specific emissions of plant', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.7, 23', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1186, 'SI-ENS-02', 'CL-SI-ENS-01', '2', 'Promoting investment for ensuring reliable supply for thermal power plants', 'Technological upgrading of thermal power plants', 'Promoting investment for ensuring reliable supply', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-01', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Adequate capacities, import independence', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.7, 23', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1187, 'SI-ENS-03', 'CL-SI-ENS-01', '3', 'Regulation of energy markets', 'Technological upgrading of thermal power plants', 'Regulation of energy markets', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-01', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Competitiveness of markets', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.7, 23', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1188, 'SI-ENS-04', 'CL-SI-ENS-02', '4', 'System of guaranteed purchase prices for CHP in district heating', 'Promoting cogeneration in district heating', 'The main instrument for promoting cogeneration is guaranteed purchase and the system of guaranteed purchase prices, the purpose of which is to use purchase prices higher than market prices to create a favourable environment for building new capacities of both combined heat and power generation and renewable source exploitation.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-02', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Cogenerated electricity, installed capacity', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.8, 23', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1189, 'SI-ENS-05', 'CL-SI-ENS-02', '5', 'Certification of energy source for CHP in district heating', 'Promoting cogeneration in district heating', 'Certification of energy source for CHP', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-02', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Cogenerated electricity, installed capacity', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.8, 23', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1190, 'SI-ENS-06', 'CL-SI-ENS-02', '6', 'Financial incentives for CHP in district heating', 'Promoting cogeneration in district heating', 'Financial incentives for the preparation of investments allocated by the Department of Efficient Energy Use and Renewable Energy Sources (EEU and RES), as well as favourable loans allocated by the Slovenian Ecological Fund.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-02', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Cogenerated electricity, installed capacity', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.8, 23', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1191, 'SI-ENS-07', 'CL-SI-ENS-03', '7', 'System of guaranteed purchase prices for renewable energy', 'Promoting renewable energy', 'Electricity generation from renewable energy sources will increase through the refurbishment of the existing hydroelectric power stations (HE) on the River Drava (HE Zlatoli?je and Formin) and on the River Sava (HE Medvode and Moste) and through the construction of new large-scale HE in the lower sections of the Sava (HE Blanca and Kr&scaron;ko). There are also plans to install wind generators up to 50 MW. Heat generation from RES will be increased through heat stations in district heating systems fuelled by wood biomass. Through the implementation of the planned refurbishment and construction of large hydroelectric plants, by 2012 power generation will increase by over 400 GWh, and in other smaller units by over 225 GWh. Implementation of the measures is being promoted through guaranteed purchase prices of electricity from RES and through financial incentives for investing in increased use of RES for combined heat and power generation. Slovenia also has an established system of certifying the origin of electrical energy.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-03', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Electricity generated from RES as a proportion of total electricity consumption', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.8, 23', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1192, 'SI-ENS-08', 'CL-SI-ENS-03', '8', 'Certification of energy source for renewable energy', 'Promoting renewable energy', 'Electricity generation from renewable energy sources will increase through the refurbishment of the existing hydroelectric power stations (HE) on the River Drava (HE Zlatoli?je and Formin) and on the River Sava (HE Medvode and Moste) and through the construction of new large-scale HE in the lower sections of the Sava (HE Blanca and Kr&scaron;ko). There are also plans to install wind generators up to 50 MW. Heat generation from RES will be increased through heat stations in district heating systems fuelled by wood biomass. Through the implementation of the planned refurbishment and construction of large hydroelectric plants, by 2012 power generation will increase by over 400 GWh, and in other smaller units by over 225 GWh. Implementation of the measures is being promoted through guaranteed purchase prices of electricity from RES and through financial incentives for investing in increased use of RES for combined heat and power generation. Slovenia also has an established system of certifying the origin of electrical energy.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-03', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Generated electricity, installed capacity', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.8, 24', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1193, 'SI-ENS-09', 'CL-SI-ENS-03', '9', 'Financial incentives for renewable energy', 'Promoting renewable energy', 'Electricity generation from renewable energy sources will increase through the refurbishment of the existing hydroelectric power stations (HE) on the River Drava (HE Zlatoli?je and Formin) and on the River Sava (HE Medvode and Moste) and through the construction of new large-scale HE in the lower sections of the Sava (HE Blanca and Kr&scaron;ko). There are also plans to install wind generators up to 50 MW. Heat generation from RES will be increased through heat stations in district heating systems fuelled by wood biomass. Through the implementation of the planned refurbishment and construction of large hydroelectric plants, by 2012 power generation will increase by over 400 GWh, and in other smaller units by over 225 GWh. Implementation of the measures is being promoted through guaranteed purchase prices of electricity from RES and through financial incentives for investing in increased use of RES for combined heat and power generation. Slovenia also has an established system of certifying the origin of electrical energy.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-03', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Generated electricity, installed capacity', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.8, 24', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1194, 'SI-ENS-10', 'CL-SI-ENS-04', '10', 'Voluntary agreements for increased energy efficiency in industry and construction', 'Increased energy efficiency in industry and construction', 'Various voluntary agreements are available to industry for reducing energy consumption:<br />&bull; Contract on reducing air pollution by CO2 emissions between the Ministry of the Environment and Spatial Planning (MESP) and individual entities (who undertake through the implementation of prescribed measures by 31 December 2008 to reduce total (direct and indirect) specific emissions of CO2) <br />&bull; GreenLight Programme &ndash; European voluntary initiative for energy-saving lighting<br />&bull; MotorChallenge Programme &ndash; European voluntary initiative for energy-saving electric engines <br />&bull; Introduction of energy management.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-04', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Specific CO2  emissions', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.8f, 24', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1195, 'SI-ENS-11', 'CL-SI-ENS-04', '11', 'Financial incentives for increased energy efficiency in industry and construction', 'Increased energy efficiency in industry and construction', 'A direct incentive for increasing energy efficiency in industry is also provided by financial incentives for the preparation of investments from the Department for EEU and RES at the Ministry of the Environment and Spatial Planning, as well as by favourable loans for investment in measures of efficient energy use from the Slovenian Ecological Fund.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-04', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Specific CO2  emissions', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.8f, 24', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1196, 'SI-ENS-12', 'CL-SI-ENS-04', '12', 'IPPC Regulation and EPA for increased energy efficiency in industry and construction', 'Increased energy efficiency in industry and construction', 'The following are key measures: promoting the purchase of energy efficient electric motors, frequency converters for regulating engine revolutions, energy-efficient pumps and ventilators, systems for preparing compressed air and energy-saving lighting. The Ministry of the Environment and Spatial Planning allocates subsidies for energy inspections of companies. A total of 18 inspections were subsidised in 2004.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-04', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Specific CO2  emissions', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.8f, 24', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1197, 'SI-ENS-13', 'CL-SI-ENS-04', '13', 'EMAS and ISO 14001 certificates for increased energy efficiency in industry and construction', 'Increased energy efficiency in industry and construction', 'An important place is also occupied by EMAS certificates and ISO 14001, since certificate holders must draw up a programme of reduced energy use.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CL-SI-ENS-04', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Specific CO2  emissions', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.8f, 24', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1198, 'SI-ENS-14', NULL, '14', 'System of guaranteed purchase prices for CHP in industry', 'Promotion of CHP generation in industry', 'In line with Directive 2004/8/EC on the promotion of cogeneration (hereinafter: CHP) a new support scheme is being prepared, and this will ensure adequate support for the development of new units of industrial CHP (investment and operating incentives). A further incentive is provided by exemption from payment of environmental fees for polluting the air with emissions of CO2. The expected capacity of new CHP units in industry by 2012 is 68 MWe , which would give additional electricity generation in the amount of 518 GWh.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '103', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Generated electricity, installed capacity', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.10, 25', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1199, 'SI-ENS-15', NULL, '15', 'Environmental tax on CO2', 'Replacement of fuels', 'A direct incentive for increasing the proportion of RES is provided by subsidies from the Ministry of the Environment and Spatial Planning  and favourable loans for investment from the Slovenian Ecological Fund. The Ministry of the Environment allocated 1.2 million euros in financial incentives for investments in wood biomass and other RES in 2004 for legal persons and sole traders. Additional incentives comprise trading in rights to greenhouse gas emissions, an environmental fee for polluting the air with CO2 emissions and raising the prices of fossil fuels, which raise the cost of using fossil fuels.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '214', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CO2 emissions from industry and construction, structure of final energy consumption.', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.10, 25', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1200, 'SI-ENS-16', NULL, '16', 'Financial incentives for renewable energy in industry', 'Increased use of RES (especially wood biomass) in industry', 'A direct incentive for increasing the proportion of RES is provided by subsidies from the Ministry of the Environment and Spatial Planning  and favourable loans for investment from the Slovenian Ecological Fund. The Ministry of the Environment allocated 1.2 million euros in financial incentives for investments in wood biomass and other RES in 2004 for legal persons and sole traders. Additional incentives comprise trading in rights to greenhouse gas emissions, an environmental fee for polluting the air with CO2 emissions and raising the prices of fossil fuels, which raise the cost of using fossil fuels.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Consumption of wood for heat in industry and construction, CO2 emission reduction, funds', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.10, 25', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1201, 'SI-ENS-17', NULL, '17', 'Financial incentives for renewable energy in households', 'Increased use of RES and replacing fuels for heating and preparation of sanitary hot water', 'This group of measures is aimed at increasing the proportion of heat consumption in households from renewable sources, natural gas and district heating systems which are supplied with heat from high-efficiency cogeneration or from renewable energy sources. The following measures are especially important: <br />&bull; installation of condensing and modular boilers in single and multi-home buildings, <br />&bull; installation of modern, high-efficiency wood biomass boilers in single and multi-home buildings (especially automatic woodchip and pellet stoves), <br />&bull; installation of solar systems for heating buildings and sanitary hot water in various sectors of energy consumption, <br />&bull; installation of heat stations for connection to district heating systems,<br />&bull; installation of heat pumps and <br />&bull; installation of microgeneration.<br />Promotion of these measures is provided by the MESP through non-returnable funds (in 2004 a total of 459,000 euros were distributed) and by the Slovenian Ecological Fund through favourable loans. Here, too, the effective implementation of measures requires a range of support activities as well as a consistent tax and price policy.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '255', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Production of heat from RES,<br />savings of CO2, <br />funds', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.14f, 27', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1202, 'SI-ENS-18', NULL, '18', 'CHP and renewable energy in households', 'Promoting cogeneration of electricity and heat based on RES', 'The measures in this area are as follows: installing microsystems for combined heat and power generation in buildings in the broad consumption sector, which in comparison to separate generation achieve greater efficiency and savings of primary energy, and owing to the generation of electricity at the place of consumption there are also fewer losses in distribution. There is also considerable potential in the use of small cogeneration systems (up to 1 MW), including in those sectors which the current scheme of guaranteed purchase prices does not cover (in residential settlements which are not included in public district heating systems and in the service sector). There are also possibilities for larger CHP systems in the service sector, especially in hospitals and tourist facilities (pools), and there is considerable potential for trigeneration. Cogeneration from renewable energy sources is topical primarily in agriculture and municipal service activities (exploiting landfill gas and treatment facility gas). Owing to its importance in the future, a special place among the measures is held by the promotion of power generation in photovoltaic systems. The instruments for implementing these measures involve direct financial incentives, favourable investment loans and a fixed purchase price for electricity. An important position is also occupied by support activities in the form of informational and promotional actions, demonstration projects and consistent, stimulative tax (excise, environmental taxes) and pricing policies.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '70', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Final consumption generated electricity in broad consumption, Saving of emissions, Funds, Certificates issued', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.15, 27', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1203, 'CL-SI-ENS-01', 'CL-SI-ENS-01', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '105', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1204, 'CL-SI-ENS-02', 'CL-SI-ENS-02', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '8', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1205, 'CL-SI-ENS-03', 'CL-SI-ENS-03', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '205', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1206, 'CL-SI-ENS-04', 'CL-SI-ENS-04', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '193', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1207, 'SI-TRA-01', NULL, '19', 'EU strategy for reducing emissions from private motor vehicles', 'Reducing emissions from private motor vehicles', 'The EU strategy for reducing CO2 emissions from private vehicles and improving fuel economy is based on three pillars: <br />&bull; the obligations of the automobile industry regarding fuel economy improvements,<br />&bull; labelling fuel economy on new private motor vehicles and <br />&bull; promoting fuel efficiency in vehicles through tax measures<br />The cornerstone of the strategy is the obligation of the European (ACEA), Japanese (JAMA) and Korean (KAMA) associations of automobile manufacturers to achieve total average CO2 emissions from new vehicles in the EU-15 of 140 g CO2/km by 2008 (ACEA) or by 2009 (JAMA and KAMA), and 120g CO2/year by 2010 (ACEA) or by 2012 (JAMA, KAMA). Labelling the fuel economy of new private vehicles was introduced through the Rules on informing consumers of fuel economy and emissions of CO2 from new private vehicles of 2003.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '467', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Specific emissions of CO2 (g/km) from new private motor vehicles', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.10, 25', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1208, 'SI-TRA-02', NULL, '20', 'Public Passenger Transport Act', 'Promoting public passenger transport', 'In order to achieve a satisfactory level of mobility (use of public passenger transport) the Resolution on the Transport Policy of the Republic of Slovenia proposes the following measures:<br />&bull; Improving the connections between various types of transport (railway, road, bicycle, pedestrian) by establishing intermodal terminals (transfer points), <br />&bull; The introduction of single tickets, <br />&bull; Establishing information centres which will offer information on all types of transport, with public awareness raising and education, <br />&bull; Ensuring punctuality, reliability and accessibility (ensuring appropriate routes for public passenger transport).<br />Single tickets were introduced with the Road Transport Act, which was adopted at the end of 2006. Actual use of the system of single tickets will be regulated by an implementing regulation.<br />On the local level, for instance, the Strategy of Transport Development of the City of Ljubljana envisages the fulfilment of the following subprogrammes:<br />&bull; A programme of constructing city tram lines with connections to the railways, and development of a regional system of &ldquo;park and ride&rdquo; for cars (and park and bike for cyclists),<br />&bull; Internationalisation of external costs (&ldquo;road pricing&rdquo;),<br />&bull; Expansion of areas for non-motorised transport,<br />&bull; More effective control over non-motorised transport.<br />Furthermore a new public passenger transport act is being drafted, and this will change the existing system of subsidies for public transport. The current system allocates subsidies by number of kilometres travelled, while the new system will allocate subsidies by number of passengers carried, which will provide an incentive for companies performing public transport services to gain new passengers.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '421', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.11f, 25', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1209, 'SI-TRA-03', NULL, '21', 'Resolution on Transport Policy', 'Transfer transit from road to rail', 'The Resolution on the Transport Policy of the Republic of Slovenia envisages the following important measures in the area of freight transport:<br />&bull; Fiscal policy measures and other measures to promote intermodality and for steering the transport system towards modern solutions in supply chains,<br />&bull; Promoting the development of logistical centres, transhipment terminals and intermodal hubs,<br />&bull; A system of mutually comparable user fees for transport infrastructure, which will ensure efficient exploitation of the entire transport infrastructure while taking into account threshold social costs generated by the individual transport system and the user,<br />&bull; Ensuring the conditions for competition in the transport market and promoting integrated logistical services in terms of planning comprehensive external logistics, the cooperation of industry and transporters and managing supply chains.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '520', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Number of ton kilometres rail/road', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.12, 26', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1210, 'SI-TRA-04', NULL, '22', 'Excise Duty Act', 'Replacing fossil fuels with biofuels', 'Through an amendment to the excise duty act in December 2003, biofuels used as motor fuel were defined as excise products with a duty rate of 0%. The next step in promoting the use of biofuels was taken with the transposition into Slovenian law of the EU directive on the promotion of biofuels and other renewable fuels for transport, which encourages Member States to increase the proportion of biofuels in the total of fuels used for transport to 2% by the end of 2005 and to 5.75% by the end of 2010. This transposition was effected through the Rules on the content of biofuels in fuels for vehicle engines (Official Gazette of the Republic of Slovenia, No 83/2005 (108/2005 - revised). The Rules set out the minimum annual average content of biofuels in all fuels placed on the market for motor fuels in the territory of Slovenia, with a minimum of 1.2% in 2006, 2% in 2007, 3% in 2008, 4% in 2009 and 5% in 2010. Ensuring the minimum content of biofuels is the obligation of motor fuel distributors.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '247', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Proportion (%) of biofuels in the consumption of motor fuels', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.12, 26', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1211, 'SI-ENC-01', NULL, '23', 'Legislation in the area of energy performance of buildings', 'Energy rehabilitation of buildings', 'The energy rehabilitation of buildings comprises measures for the shell of the building (heat insulation of the exterior fa&ccedil;ade and loft and replacement of windows) and optimisation of cooling and heating systems, through technological solutions such as thermostatic valves, regulation and hydraulic balancing of heating systems, regulation of heating systems relative to the exterior temperature for all buildings; measuring and charging energy costs by actual use; replacing heat substations in district systems with more efficient ones; energy efficient pumps in heating systems etc. installed by building owners.<br />The consumption of energy in newly constructed buildings is limited by regulations: the standards  from 2002 reduce the consumption of energy by 30% compared to the previous standard (from 1981), while a new regulation is being drafted (and should be adopted during 2007) which will ensure a further 30% reduction in energy consumption (transposition of Directive 2002/91/EC on the energy performance of buildings).<br />In the rehabilitation of buildings owned by the state, the state decides directly on the implementation of energy rehabilitation. There are instruments available for this sector such as contractually guaranteed energy savings and green public procurement. Within the framework of this measure, promoting the construction of passive and low-energy buildings is also important.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '105', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Adoption and monitoring of implementation of regulation (No. or proportion of energy ID cards)', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.13f, 26', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1212, 'SI-ENC-02', NULL, '24', 'Financial incentives for energy rehabilitation of buildings', 'Energy rehabilitation of buildings', 'Through direct financial incentives (in 2004 a total of 267,000 euros were distributed) and favourable loans the state is guiding and ensuring that improvements are implemented earlier than would otherwise be the case, with regular improvements of the housing stock or whereby alongside regular improvements to the housing stock, there is also energy rehabilitation which meets the standards or which exceeds the standards. The consumption of energy in newly constructed buildings is limited by regulations: the standards  from 2002 reduce the consumption of energy by 30% compared to the previous standard (from 1981), while a new regulation is being drafted (and should be adopted during 2007) which will ensure a further 30% reduction in energy consumption (transposition of Directive 2002/91/EC on the energy performance of buildings).<br />The effectiveness of direct financial incentives requires a range of support activities for the identification and preparation of projects (model projects, promotion and training, consultation) as well as the implementation of pricing and tax policy.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '217', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Rehabilitated surface, <br />energy savings, <br />savings of CO2,<br />funds', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.13f, 27', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1213, 'SI-ENC-03', NULL, '25', 'Directive on energy end-use efficiency and energy services', 'Energy rehabilitation of buildings', 'An important instrument is the implementation of the directive on efficient final energy consumption and energy services, whereby Member States are bound to set outline targets of reducing energy consumption by 9% in nine years. Energy savings will start to be measures on 1 January 2008. The public sector is also especially highlighted in the directive. The directive binds Member States to:<br />&bull; ensure that energy distributors, system operators of the distribution network and retail energy companies offer energy services and energy inspections or that they contribute to an energy efficiency fund,<br />&bull; establish a system for training, certification and/or accreditation of the providers of energy services, energy inspections and measures to increase energy efficiency,<br />&bull; remove legal barriers limiting the use of innovative methods of financing, such as contractual reduction of energy costs, and to provide sample contracts for such instruments,<br />&bull; in the tariffs for transmission and distribution of energy remove incentives which unnecessarily increase the quantity of energy transmitted,<br />&bull; set up high-quality programmes of energy inspections aimed at determining possible measures for increasing energy efficiency,<br />&bull; ensure that all end users of electricity, natural gas, district heating and hot sanitary water are equipped with individual meters which display precisely the actual quantity and flow of energy consumption,<br />&bull; through bills or other documents in assessing energy charges communicate to final consumers information on the valid actual prices and actual energy consumption, on the characteristics of their energy consumption and on energy efficiency measures.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '% final energy saving', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.13f, 27', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1214, 'SI-ENC-04', NULL, '26', 'Energy efficiency in households', 'Increased energy efficiency in households', 'The following are key measures: promoting the purchase of energy-saving household appliances (class A and better refrigerators, freezers, washing machines and dishwashers with an average of 35% lower energy consumption for the same service than appliances in use), promoting the purchase of energy-saving light bulbs (70%), while there is also major potential in efficient use of electricity for heating and preparation of sanitary hot water or in exchanging fuel and reducing the consumption of energy by appliances in standby mode through proper management and the purchase of appliances with low consumption in standby mode (under 30 W per household). In services, an important measure is promoting the purchase and replacement of energy-saving light bulbs and replacement of energy wasting units for ventilation and air conditioning. This area also includes the installation of energy-saving light bulbs and lighting regulators for public lighting.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '305', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Energy consumption savings achieved through allocated subsidies, emission savings, proportion of class A appliances', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.16, 28', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1215, 'SI-IND-01', NULL, '27', 'IPPC regulation and EPA for aluminium', 'Adaptation of aluminium production to BAT', 'In 2006 the process was started for halting electrolysis B, and this should be concluded by 31 October 2007, since electrolysis does not meet the standards of best available technologies set out in the reference documents for obtaining environmental permits deriving from the IPPC Directive. In 2005, when electrolysis B was still fully operational, Slovenia produced 120,000 tons of primary aluminium. In 2008, when only electrolysis C will be operating, a total of 85,000 tons of primary aluminium will be produced. The closure of electrolysis B will directly contribute to the reduction of CO2 and PFC emissions from the process, and to the reduction of electricity consumption, which will indirectly contribute to a reduction of CO2 emissions from electricity generation.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '159', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Specific emissions of greenhouse gases in aluminium production', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.16, 28', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1216, 'SI-IND-02', NULL, '28', 'Coolant emissions from refrigeration, freezing and air conditioning appliances and removal of coolants from obsolete appliances', 'Reducing emissions of coolants', 'The biggest source of HFC emissions is air conditioners in vehicles, which have a high leakage rate. Emissions from this source will be reduced through implementation of Directive 2006/40/EC relating to emissions from air conditioning systems in motor vehicles, which after 4 July 2009  will permit the registration of new vehicles if their installed air conditioning contains coolant with a greenhouse potential of less than 150 or if the leakage of coolant from the air conditioner does not exceed 40 g  a year. The other important requirement of the directive, which will enter into force on 1 January 2017, is the prohibition on registration of vehicles which have installed air conditioning that contains coolant with a greenhouse potential greater than 150. Moreover in 2006 the EU adopted the Regulation on certain fluorinated greenhouse gases (No 842/2006), which will contribute to reducing emissions from large stationary cooling systems , since it requires regular control of system emissions, education of experts for managing such appliances and the collection of coolant from obsolete appliances. In addition to the aforementioned regulation, the removal of coolant from obsolete appliances is regulated by the Decree on the method, subject and conditions for performing the commercial public service of managing end of life motor vehicles and the Rules on managing waste electrical and electronic equipment.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '32', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Implementation of measures provided by the regulation', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.16f, 28f', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1217, 'SI-WAM-01', NULL, '29', 'Decree on landfill of waste, Decree on environmental tax for environmental pollution caused by waste disposal', 'Rehabilitation of existing and construction of new landfills in line with EU standards &ndash; capture of landfill gas', 'The Decree on the landfill of waste requires all landfill sites to have a system for capture and appropriate management of landfill gas by the end of 2005. In 2003 the capture and use of landfill gas was provided only at the three biggest landfills (Ljubljana&ndash;Barje, Maribor&ndash;Pobre≈æje, Celje&ndash;Bukov≈ælak), which as a proportional share of the population represent about 30% of the entire population. In 2003 a total of 15% of landfill gas was captured and used for energy. Another important source of biogas is the treatment of waste water in treatment facilities. There are plans for the future installation of additional treatment facilities and biogas power stations. The Decree on environmental tax for environmental pollution caused by waste disposal, which introduced the payment of taxes paid by landfill managers for pollution resulting from waste disposal, envisages exemptions from the payment of taxes in the event of implementing works to reduce the burden on the environment. Moreover, the funds collected through environmental taxes for waste disposal can be used for implementing measures from the environmental action plan in the area of urban waste disposal.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '105', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.17f, 29', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1218, 'SI-WAM-02', NULL, '30', 'Rules for biodigradable waste', 'Reducing disposed quantities of biodegradable waste through composting or processing into biofuels', 'The Decree on the management of separately collected fractions in performing the public service of urban waste management was adopted in 2001, and under this regulation municipal service companies had to establish a system of collecting and removing separate fractions throughout the country by the end of 2003. Systems were set up for the separate collection of glass, packaging, paper and cardboard. The Decree on the management of packaging and packaging waste was adopted in 2006, and this sets the following targets: <br />&bull; at least 60% of the total mass of packaging waste must be subject to packaging waste recovery, including energy recovery;<br />&bull; between at least a minimum of 55% and maximum of 80% of the total mass of packaging waste must be recycled;<br />&bull;  at least the following recycling rates must be ensured for individual types of packaging material contained in the total mass of packaging waste:<br />? 60% of the mass for glass,<br />? 60% of the mass for paper and cardboard,<br />? 50% of the mass for metal,<br />? 22.5% of the mass for plastic, with only material being recycled back into plastic being taken into consideration,<br />? 15% of the mass for wood.<br />The Decree on the landfill of waste (Official Gazette of the Republic of Slovenia, No 32/2006) was adopted in 2006, and this sets the maximum quantity of disposed biodegradable content in urban waste that may be deposited annually in all landfills in the territory of Slovenia. For 2010 the quantity is 148 kt of biodegradable waste. The Rules on the management of organic kitchen waste were adopted in 2004, and these required by the end of 2004 the separate collection of kitchen waste from catering establishments, and by the end of 2005 the separate collection of kitchen waste from households and the processing of collected waste in a municipal composter. Furthermore the Rules on the management of waste edible oils and fats were adopted in 2004, and these provide that a system must be in place by the end of 2004 for the collection and processing of edible oils and fats from catering establishments.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '40', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.18, 29', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1219, 'SI-AGR-01', NULL, '31', 'Anaerobic Digesters', 'Promoting anaerobic digesters for producing biogas', 'This measure has a dual effect, since the construction of biogas facilities in agriculture will reduce methane emissions, while in the energy sector there will be an improvement in the supply of renewable energy sources. The main limiting factor in implementing the measure is the fragmented nature of Slovenian animal husbandry, with the construction of biogas facilities only being economical on large holdings. With increasing prices of energy, interest in producing biogas rises. The instruments for implementing this measure are as follows: subsidising the construction of biogas facilities, subsidising electricity from biogas and providing information and education to potential constructors. In subsidising the construction of biogas facilities, those facilities that will generate biogas chiefly from animal manure should take priority over facilities that will produce biogas from other plant material.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '16', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Number of animals being raised with digesters set up', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.19, 30', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1220, 'SI-AGR-02', NULL, '32', 'Pasture raising of beef cattle', 'Reducing methane emissions', 'This measure contributes to reducing methane emissions which arise in the storage of animal manures. Pasture stockfarming is also economically attractive, but its pursuit in Slovenia is seriously limited by climate conditions (long winters, unevenly distributed precipitation), the fragmentation of land and the high average distance of pasture land from farms. An important instrument for increasing the proportion of animals in pasture is promoting expert and advisory work in the area of pasture stockfarming and simplifying procedures in agricultural land consolidation. Another important factor is the appropriate solving of the issue of large carnivores spreading into areas suitable for pasturing. Any inexpert transition to very extensive methods of pasturing carries with it the danger of greenhouse gas emissions per unit of production (milk and meat) increasing.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '15', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Number of beef cattle raised in pasture', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.19, 30', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1221, 'SI-AGR-03', NULL, '33', 'Education on rational fertilising, cofinancing soil analyses', 'Rational fertilising of agricultural plants', 'The aim of the measure is to improve the effectiveness of the nitrogen cycle on farms and in this way to reduce the need for nitrogen from mineral fertilisers, which in turn reduces emissions of nitrous oxide. The main instrument for improving the effectiveness of the nitrogen cycle is the promotion of integrated farming, which must be designed in such a way as to enable the return of plant nutrients from animal husbandry into plant production. Another important factor is the promotion of expert and advisory work in the area of managing animal manures and plant nutrition. In the introduction of rational fertiliser use, the major obstacle is again the fragmented nature of farms, since a large number of farmers need to be educated for a relatively small effect, while certain procedures such as a rapid soil tests to determine the nitrogen supply for plants are too expensive for small parcels.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '37', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Use of mineral fertilisers', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.19f, 30', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1222, 'SI-LUC-01', NULL, '34', 'Forest Development Programme in Slovenia', 'Increasing of CO2 sinks', 'Since the base year of 1986, the surface area of forest in Slovenia has increased by 105,000 ha, which means that the surface area of forest has increased by an average of 5,500 ha annually. Assuming that such a trend of increasing surface area will continue, we may conclude that in 2020 Slovenia will have more than 1,244,000 ha of forest, representing more than 61% of the entire national territory. The forest growing stock increased by 102% in the period from 1960 to 2003, which translates into an average annual growth of 2.37%. The increased growing stock in forests is a result of the planned management of forests, and partly a result of changed methodology for determining forest growing stock. The Forest Development Programme (Official Gazette of the Republic of Slovenia, No 14/1996) provides that in guiding the development of forests with emphasised ecological and social functions and in guiding their simultaneous and coordinated use, the highest possible growing stock of stands should be attained, except in extreme growing conditions and in protected forests, where structural diversity takes distinct precedence. The currently estimated CO2 sink in Slovenian forests is four times higher than the currently recognised sink (1.3 Mt CO2 annually). Inasmuch as there will be no major natural disasters and rapid climate changes, we may assert with great probability that the status of forest sinks will remain the same over the next 15 years, or will not be reduced in any significant degree.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1320', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CO2 sink', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.20, 30', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
