(1223, 'SI-CRS-01', NULL, '35', 'Emissions Trading', 'Reducing CO2 emissions', 'In the first period, 2005 to 2007, the National Plan for Allocation of Emission Coupons included 96 operators of heating and combustion facilities, who were allocated a total of 26,217,984 t CO2 for the entire three-year period, or an average of 8,739,328 tCO2 a year. The Slovenian Government adopted the National Plan for Allocation of Emission Coupons for the period 2005 to 2007 at the end of September 2004.<br />In September 2006 the Ministry of the Environment and Spatial Planning, in cooperation with the Ministry of the Economy and the Ministry of Finance, drafted the National Plan for Allocation of Emission Coupons for the period from 2008 to 2012 (hereinafter: National Plan). In accordance with the second paragraph of Article 126 of the Environmental Protection Act, the National Plan includes all facilities for which the operators had obtained permits for greenhouse gas emissions by 1 January 2006, pursuant to Article 118 of the Environmental Protection Act, and a use permit under the regulations on the building of structures. The entire quantity of emission coupons that are allocated to operators for the entire period from 2008 to 2012 amounts to 41,494,687 t CO2 or an average of 8,298,937 tCO2 a year. Existing facility operators are allocated an average of 8,167,941 t CO2 of which 5,817,000 t CO2 are for thermal power plants and thermal CHP plants, 205,853 t CO2 are for heating plants and 2,145,088 t CO2 for industry. A total of 130,996 t CO2 are envisaged for operators of new facilities.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1313', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'CO2 emission reduction', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.20f, 30', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1224, 'SI-CRS-02', NULL, '36', 'Change of excise duty and Environmental tax on CO2', 'Reducing CO2 emissions', 'The environmental tax for polluting the air with emissions of CO2 was introduced back on 1 January 1997 pursuant to the Decree on tax for polluting the air with emissions of CO2 in accordance with Article 80 of the Environmental Protection Act (Official Gazette of the Republic of Slovenia, Nos 32/93, 44/95 &ndash; decision of the Constitutional Court, 1/)6,9/99 &ndash; decision of the Constitutional Court, 56/99, 22/00 and 67/02). This instrument was introduced with the aim of internalising the external costs of air pollution load by emissions of CO2 and should as an economic instrument bring about the reduction of air pollution load by emissions of CO2 and consequently reduce the air pollution load. The environmental tax is paid for the use of fuels and the incineration of combustible organic substances. The basis for charging environmental tax for polluting the air with CO2 emissions is the sum of units of load of the purchased quantity of fuel or the units of load of burned combustible organic substances. The price per unit of load is determined by the Slovenian Government at 16 &euro;/t CO2. With the aim of promoting the implementation of measures, the legal basis for the environmental tax includes exemptions in two cases: <br />&bull; Operators of facilities for combined heat and power generation,<br />&bull; Operators of facilities who in relation to the operation of such facility has concluded a contract on the reduction of air pollution by CO2 with the ministry competent for environmental protection.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Revenue from environmental taxes and excise duty on energy', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.21f, 31', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1225, 'SI-CRS-03', NULL, '37', 'JI and CDM', 'Reducing CO2 emissions', 'In Slovenia the area of joint investments is regulated by the provisions of the Environmental Protection Act (Official Gazette of the Republic of Slovenia, No 39/06 - official consolidated text, hereinafter: Environmental Protection Act). In accordance with Article 140 of the Environmental Protection Act, joint investment is a project activity which is approved by one or more Parties to Annex 1 of the Kyoto Protocol for carrying out a joint implementation project under Article 6 of the Kyoto Protocol (Joint Implementation project) or Article 12 of the Kyoto Protocol (Clean Development Mechanism) and the Conclusions of the 7th COP of the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change held in December 2001 in Marrakech (hereinafter: Marrakech Conclusions). Slovenia appointed a competent coordination body for cooperation in joint investments, and provided notification of this to the secretariat of the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change; this is the Designated Focal Point for cooperation in joint implementation and the Designated National Authority for cooperation in the Clean Development Mechanism. Pursuant to Conclusion 16/CP.7 of Marrakech, the State Party must also adopt the legislative framework of the procedure for approving joint implementation projects, their monitoring and verification and the State&rsquo;s own instructions, and submit this together with the accommodated comments from those with an interest to the Secretariat of the Framework Convention. <br />In May 2006 the Slovenian Minister of the Environment and Spatial Planning signed an agreement with the Ministry of the Environment of FYR Macedonia on cooperation in the area of projects to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases. By signing the agreement, Slovenian and FYR Macedonia agreed that Macedonia would transfer its credit (&ldquo;confirmed units of reduction of greenhouse gas emissions&rdquo;) resulting from joint investments by Slovenian commercial companies in Clean Development Mechanism projects in an agreed proportion to Slovenia or to Slovenian companies. This would enable Slovenian companies to further enhance their funds invested in joint investment projects by obtaining &ldquo;credit&rdquo;, since they could sell the &ldquo;credit&rdquo; on the market of rights to greenhouse gas emissions.<br />Preparations are under way for the signing of similar agreements with other countries that meet the requirements and have ratified the Kyoto Protocol.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Emission saving through JI and CDM projects', NULL, 'SI-2008 Submission under Decision 280/2004/EC, p.22, 31', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1226, 'SK-IND-02', NULL, 'CRS-01', 'Sectoral operational program Industry and Services', 'Reduction in energy use and emissions', 'Definition of priorities and measures in 2004-2006 in the following areas: Impact of business activities on the environment - reduction by 2% in 2006 compared to 2001; <br />Reduction of energy demand in supported companies by 2,5% in 2006 compared to 2001;<br />Implement 25 projects aimed at energy savings in 2006;<br />Reduce energy and row material demand in industrial processes by 2,5% compared to 2001;<br />Reduce energy costs in 2006 by 2,5% compared to 2001.', '2003', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'average status in 2002', 'change in activity range', 'yes', 'Final report on GHG emission projections SHMI 2007', 'List of annual indicators - Annex II to Decision 2005/166/EC - table II-1 and II-2', NULL, 'SK Submission 07', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1227, 'SK-IND-03', NULL, 'IND-01', 'Reduction of releases in compliance with EU legislation', 'Recycling and ban of coolants that contain substances depleting the ozone layer', 'Based on the Act 76/1998 the methodology to control technical performance of products was endorsed. Regular inspection on sealing of cooling and air conditioning equipment is regulated by the EU directive 2037/2000/EC. CFC coolants must not be produced in Slovakia. Removed CFC coolants have to be disposed as waste. Newly produced NCFC could be used by December 2000. Other HCFC will be banned in January 2015.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0,13', NULL, '0,15', NULL, '0,14', NULL, NULL, 'WM projections', NULL, 'yes', 'Final report on GHG emission projections SHMI 2007', 'List of annual indicators - Annex II to Decision 2005/166/EC - table II-1 and II-2', NULL, 'SK Submission 07', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
